HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 943
By Boyd
A RESOLUTION to commemorate the twenty-fifth anniversary of
September 11, 2001.
WHEREAS, the lives of Americans were changed forever on September 11, 2001, when
tragic events threatened our way of life; and
WHEREAS, twenty-five years later, the people of the United States and people around
the world continue to mourn the tremendous loss of innocent life on that fateful day; and
WHEREAS, thousands of men and women in the United States Armed Forces remain in
harm's way defending our nation against those who seek to threaten the United States; and
WHEREAS, on the twenty-fifth anniversary of that tragic day, the thoughts of the people
of the United States are with all of the victims of the events of September 11, 2001; and
WHEREAS, beginning in 2002, family members who lost loved ones in the September
11, 2001, terrorist attacks began to seek a forward-looking tribute to honor the sacrifice of those
who were lost and to pay tribute to those who rose in service in response to the tragedy; and
WHEREAS, by encouraging Americans to volunteer and participate in service and
remembrance activities on the 9/11 anniversary, family members provided a productive and
respectful way to honor those who perished and rekindled the spirit of unity that swept our
nation after 9/11 to help meet the challenges we face today; and
WHEREAS, because of their efforts to build support for this idea, September 11th has
been designated as a National Day of Service and Remembrance, and proud Americans will
come together annually in communities across this country to both remember the fallen and to
volunteer for the greater good; and
WHEREAS, September 11, 2026, marks the twenty-fifth anniversary of that horrific day,
and it is most appropriate for the members of this General Assembly and the great State of
HJR0943
013225
- 1 -

Tennessee, known far and wide as the Volunteer State, to observe this special day in volunteer
service to our communities as a respectful tribute; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of those lost in the 9/11 tragedy and in service to
this great nation, as we also encourage Tennesseans to volunteer in their community as we
continue our commitment to freedom, security, and stronger communities.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
